File and Directory Management:

pwd: Print Working Directory - Shows the current directory you're in.
ls: List - Lists files and directories in the current directory.
cd: Change Directory - Navigates the file system by changing directories.
mkdir: Make Directory - Creates a new directory.
cp: Copy - Copies files and directories.
mv: Move - Moves or renames files and directories.
rm: Remove - Deletes files and directories (use with caution!).
Permissions and Ownership:

chown: Change Owner - Changes the owner of a file or directory.
chmod: Change Mode - Modifies file permissions (read, write, execute) for users, groups, and others.
Process Management:

ps: Process Status - Lists running processes.
top: Shows process activity in real-time.
kill: Terminates a process.
Text Manipulation and Searching:

cat: Concatenate - Displays the contents of a file.
grep: Global Regular Expression Print - Searches for patterns within text files.
sed: Stream Editor - Filters and modifies text content.
awk: Pattern Scanning and Processing Language - Manipulates text data based on patterns.
Package Management:

apt (Debian/Ubuntu): Advanced Package Tool - Installs, updates, and removes software packages.
yum (Red Hat/CentOS): Yellowdog Update Manager - Similar to apt for Red Hat-based distributions.
System Administration:

free: Displays information about free and used memory.
df: Disk Free - Shows disk usage for mounted file systems.
netstat: Network Statistics - Displays network connections and routing information.
ping: Network diagnostics tool to check connectivity to a host.
ssh: Secure Shell - Establishes a secure remote connection to another server.
Version Control (often used with Git):

git clone: Clones a Git repository from a remote server.
git status: Shows the current status of the working directory.
git add: Adds changes to the staging area for version control.
git commit: Creates a commit with a message describing the changes.
git push: Pushes committed changes to a remote repository.
